{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505975"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2501"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2501"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.46,0.18,0.06,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43001"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2501"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43170"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43001"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman from a nursing home is hospitalised with a 48-hour history of fevers and dyspnoea. Her medical history includes hypertension, osteoporosis and dementia. Her medications list includes hydrochlorothiazide, denosumab and aspirin. On examination, she appears confused. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60mmHg, temperature 38.8\u00b0C, respiratory rate 26/min and SpO2 is 91% on room air. Her mucous membranes appear dry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn initial investigations, her WCC is 18x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0 \u2013 11.0) and eGFR 70mL/min/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u226590). Her chest X-ray shows bilateral lower zone opacification. She is diagnosed with bacterial pneumonia and treated with oxygen, fluid resuscitation and intravenous antibiotics. Whilst she improves haemodynamically over the next 48 hours, her renal function deteriorates with eGFR measuring at 25mL/min/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u226590).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Given the likely diagnosis, which of the following would be seen on urine microscopy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transitional epithelial cells","Brown granular casts","Erythrocyte casts","Waxy casts","Leukocyte casts"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u2019s presentation is consistent with acute tubular necrosis (ATN). ATN is the most common cause of intrinsic acute kidney injury. It is most common in hospitalised patients and is associated with high morbidity and mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon aetiologies of ATN include an ischaemic event, nephrotoxins or a combination of both \u2013 as in this case. Ischaemic causes of ATN include hypovolaemic states such as diarrhoea, vomiting, haemorrhage, dehydration, burns or renal losses; while sepsis is also an important cause of renal hypoperfusion. Nephrotoxins implicated in ATN include drugs such as aminoglycosides, radiocontrast media, sulfa- drugs, acyclovir, cisplatin, calcineurin inhibitors among others. This case likely has systemic hypoxia stemming from acute illness as well as possible antibiotic nephrotoxicity.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHistory and physical examination in a patient with ATN should focus on identifying the aetiology, while the investigations aim to differentiated ATN from other causes of intra-renal AKI. Urine microscopy in ATN will classically show \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0027muddy brown\u0027 granular casts\u003C/strong\u003E or renal epithelial tubular cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mainstay of management of ATN is the removal of any offending agents and treatment of the underlying cause. Renal replacement therapy may be indicated in cases of hyperkalaemia, uraemia or acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary casts are formed in the renal tubules due to an aggregation of protein. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransitional epithelial cells \u003C/strong\u003Eline the urinary tract from the renal pelvis to the distal part of the male urethra and the base of the bladder in females - their presence in urine may indicate urinary tract infection or malignancy, however, they are more commonly associated with urethral or ureteral catheterisation. Hyaline casts are a nonspecific finding which may be found in normal urine as well as dehydration or acute, pre-renal acute kidney injury. Broad and \u003Cstrong\u003Ewaxy casts\u003C/strong\u003E are acellular and seen in chronic kidney disease and are comprised of a glycoprotein matrix with degraded protein which is formed in atrophic tubules. \u003Cstrong\u003EErythrocyte casts\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in glomerulonephritis and \u003Cstrong\u003Eleukocyte casts\u003C/strong\u003E suggest tubulointerstitial inflammation that may be seen in glomerulonephritis, pyelonephritis or interstitial nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute tubular necrosis is associated with \u0027muddy brown\u0027 granular casts on microscopy, with or without renal epithelial tubular cells"],"references":["Hanif MO, Bali A, Ramphul K. Acute Renal Tubular Necrosis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507815/#:~:text=Acute%20tubular%20necrosis%20is%20precipitated,or%20toxic%20event%20or%20sepsis.\u0026text=Heme%20pigment%2Dcontaining%20proteins%20such,tubular%20obstruction%2C%20or%20renal%20vasoconstriction.","Perazella MA, Coca SG, Kanbay M, Brewster UC, Parikh CR. Diagnostic value of urine microscopy for differential diagnosis of acute kidney injury in hospitalized patients. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008;3(6):1615-9. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2572284/","Salzberg DJ, Weir MR. 38 - The kidney and rheumatic disease. In: Hochberg MC, Silman AJ, Smolen JS, Weinblatt ME, Weisman MH, editors. Rheumatology (Sixth Edition). Philadelphia: Mosby; 2015;286-97."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2501"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-27T17:42:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-27T17:42:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2501"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43001"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"http